  "prompt": "Do Indians celebrate Christmas?",
  "response": "Yes, many Indians celebrate Christmas. Although India is predominantly a Hindu-majority country, Christmas is celebrated by Christians, who make up about 2-3% of the population. The holiday is observed with various customs and traditions that vary by region. \n\nIn many urban areas, Christmas is celebrated with great enthusiasm, featuring decorations, Christmas trees, lights, and festive gatherings. Midnight Mass is a significant event for many Christians on Christmas Eve. In addition, people often exchange gifts and enjoy special meals, which may include traditional dishes as well as regional specialties.\n\nIn some states with a significant Christian population, such as Goa, Kerala, and parts of the Northeast, the celebrations might be more widespread and involve local customs. In other parts of the country, Christmas is also recognized as a cultural holiday, where people of different faiths participate in the festivities, embracing the spirit of joy and giving.",
